PART B — PEER REVIEW OF SwarmGPT's swarm_spatial_hypercycle.py
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

SwarmGPT, welcome back. Genuinely glad to see you in the round. You
got the discrete Laplacian right (`(roll + roll + roll + roll)/4 −
self` is the proper mean-of-neighbors-minus-self form, equivalent to
mine up to a factor of 4 in time scale). But three findings:

FINDING 1 — `normalize()` MAKES THE WHOLE EXPERIMENT VACUOUS.

  After every step you call

      def normalize(self):
          total = self.grid.sum(axis=2, keepdims=True)
          self.grid /= total

  This forces the per-cell sum of (cycle species + parasite) to
  exactly 1 at every site at every step. Mass is rigidly conserved
  per cell. Under that constraint, the parasite cannot collapse in
  mass — only in fraction. Your "parasite=0.4 vs hypercycle=0.6"
  comparison is meaningful, but the survive-vs-die framing of the
  test is gone: nothing can ever go extinct in absolute mass terms,
  because the constraint forbids it.

  Boerlijst–Hogeweg 1991 explicitly does NOT impose per-cell
  normalization. They use a global "death rate" φ to keep total mass
  bounded, but local cells are allowed to be empty or saturated.
  That asymmetry is what lets spiral wavefronts physically RUN AWAY
  from parasites — empty space ahead of the wave is what the
  parasite cannot keep up with. Your normalization fills that empty
  space by fiat.

FINDING 2 — YOUR MUTATION OPERATOR IS NOT MUTATION.

      leak = self.mut * G[:, :, i]
      newG[:, :, i] -= leak
      newG[:, :, (i + 1) % self.n] += leak

  This is a directed conveyor belt around the cycle. Every species
  ALWAYS leaks into the next cycle member with probability `mut`,
  never into anything else, never to/from the parasite. That is not
  mutation; it is a biased flow that happens to look symmetric on
  the cycle and asymmetric everywhere else. Real Hamming-distance
  mutation (the kind that connects to my Event 15b quasispecies
  drop) is undirected. As written, your "mutation" actually ASSISTS
  the cycle by pumping it forward and DOES NOTHING to seed parasite
  drift. Wire-in-correctness, not concept-correctness.

FINDING 3 — NO `proof_of_property()`.

  Same critique as GROK's Finding 2. You print ASCII at the end and
  print totals every 100 steps, but nothing asserts that spirals
  emerged or that parasites were excluded. The judge has nothing to
  verify. "If you wire this into SwarmRL" is a future-work bullet,
  not a proof.

